Lesson: Using Property Wrappers
Property wrappers allow you to extract common behavioral logic (like clamping, validation, or logging) into a reusable wrapper that can be applied to any property using an '@' attribute.

Core Concepts:
1. Syntactic Sugar: When you mark a property with '@Wrapper', Swift automatically creates an instance of the wrapper type to manage that property's storage.
2. Interface: You interact with the property normally (e.g., 'furnace.heat'), but every read and write goes through the wrapper's internal logic.
3. Reusability: Instead of writing clamping logic in every struct, you write it once in a '@propertyWrapper' and reuse it everywhere.

Example:
    struct Furnace {
        @Clamped(0...100) var heat = 120
    }
    // heat is automatically 100

Note: Property wrappers are a powerful way to keep your data models clean and declarative.

solution:
import Foundation

@propertyWrapper
struct Clamped {
    private var value: Int
    private let range: ClosedRange<Int>

    var wrappedValue: Int {
        get { value }
        set { value = min(max(newValue, range.lowerBound), range.upperBound) }
    }

    init(wrappedValue: Int, _ range: ClosedRange<Int>) {
        self.range = range
        self.value = min(max(wrappedValue, range.lowerBound), range.upperBound)
    }
}

struct Furnace {
    @Clamped(0...100) var heat = 120
}

var furnace = Furnace()
print(furnace.heat)

