Lesson: Building Custom Wrappers
To create your own property wrapper, you define a structure or class marked with the '@propertyWrapper' attribute. This type must have a property named 'wrappedValue', which is what the outside world interacts with.

Core Concepts:
1. wrappedValue: This is the only required property. It defines the logic for reading and writing the value.
2. Initializers: You can provide custom initializers to set up the wrapper (e.g., setting a range for clamping or an initial value).
3. Encapsulation: Use private storage (e.g., 'private var value') inside the wrapper to hold the actual data, while exposing it safely through 'wrappedValue'.

Example:
    @propertyWrapper
    struct Lowercased {
        private var value: String = ""
        var wrappedValue: String {
            get { value }
            set { value = newValue.lowercased() }
        }
        init(wrappedValue: String) { self.wrappedValue = wrappedValue }
    }

Note: Custom wrappers allow you to define highly specialized data handling rules that are easy to apply across your project.

